5","Abt 1364":"about 1364","1398":"1398","1364":"1364","about 1340":"about 1340","Cubley, Derbyshire, England":"Little Cubley, Derbyshire, England","Dukinfield, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Dukinfield, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Dokinfield, Lancaster, Eng":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Aldford, Cheshire, England":"Aldford, Cheshire, England","Aldford Castle, Runcorn, Cheshire, England":"Runcorn, Cheshire, England","Brackley, Northampton, england":"Brackley, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Arderne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Ardern  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ardern","meanings":["English: locative name variant of   Arden  . Arden in Cheshire is recorded as  <i>Arderne</i> in 1260, and Arden in Warwicks is recorded as  <i>Arderne</i> in 1200."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":42,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":115,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes Arderne was born about 1340, in Aldford, Cheshire, England. She married John de Dukinfield in 1360, in Runcorn, Cheshire, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1340–":"umbes 1340–Surnud","1338–1401":"1338–1401","1360–1435":"1360–1435","1360–Male":"1360–Surnud","1362–Male":"1362–Surnud","1364–1398":"1364–1398","1340–Female":"1340–Surnud","about 1360":"umbes 1360","abt 1360":"1360","1340":"1340","1362":"1362","abt 1362":"umbes 1362","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1338":"1338","Abt 1360":"umbes 1360","1435":"1435","1401":"1401","1455":"1455","Abt 1364":"umbes 1364","1398":"1398","1364":"1364","about 1340":"umbes 1340","Cubley, Derbyshire, England":"Little Cubley, Derbyshire, England","Dukinfield, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Dukinfield, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Dokinfield, Lancaster, Eng":"Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Aldford, Cheshire, England":"Aldford, Cheshire, England","Aldford Castle, Runcorn, Cheshire, England":"Runcorn, Cheshire, England","Brackley, Northampton, england":"Brackley, Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1340–":"noin 1340–Kuollut","1338–140